comments.message:
> hwcallout indicates we have to call out something other than FAPI targets.

What you mean by "something other than FAPI targets."? Non-FAPI (aka plat-specific targets)?

I am a bit concerned about the case where the reference target (FAPI and Non-FAPI target, respective FRU Location code will be identified by openpower::phal::pdbg::getLocationCode())) is available in the device tree and that is different than the CDG (Callout/Deconfigure/Guard) target means, we will lose that case to handle, right? The current code will support that, right? 

If you are looking for the clock error alone to handle based on the reference target then, that should decide by the PHAL layer as you did `hwCallout.isPlanarCallout` i.e you should not add the reference target in the plat layer if you want to callout the planer instead of the reference target since you indicated by the `isPlanarCallout`, right?

I think we could do like below

```
if (hwCallout.isPlanarCallout)
{
   calloutPlanar();
   // comments to why continue to other targets
   // Note, We should not continue if we want to callout the planar along with reference target (different than planar)
   continue;
}
```


and noted, reference target and CDG target are the same in the https://github.com/open-power/pub-ekb/blob/main-p10/chips/p10/procedures/xml/error_info/p10_clock_test_errors.xml#L53? Do you know why? I think we will callout the same target twice.

Not all IPL_ERR_ATTR_READ_FAIL and IPL_ERR_ATTR_WRITE failures needed the plat specific error handling . This is genric error used in IPL. Prefer to call  processPlatBootError only for error type is plat/specific errors. 

Since you already passing hwp structure  from ipl , Add the these resoncode info in special reason codes in HWP_ErrorInfo structure  and alway's return IPL_ERR_PLAT from ipl incase special processing required.

struc HWP_ErrorInfo
{
    // To get hwp return code which is defined in error xml for
    // each error
    std::string rc;

    // To get return code desciption
    std::string rc_desc;. 
}

